I attribute the good and evil Operations of the fore-mentioned Steams, rather in general to the conent of the parts that make up the genus Nervoum, than to any hidden Sympathy or Antipathy betwixt them and the Womb, not only for other reaons, not proper to be inited on here, but becaue I have known Odours have notable Effects even upon Men. I know a very eminent peron, a Traveller, and a man of a trong contitution, but coniderably Sanguine, who is put into violent Head-aches by the Smell of Musk. And I remember, that one day being
with him and a great many other men of note about a Publick Affair, a man that had a parcel of Musk about him, having an occaion to make an application to us, this peron was o diordered by the mell, which to mot of us was delightful, that in pight of his Civility he was reduc'd to make us an Apology, and end the perfumed man out of the room, notwithtanding whoe reces this peron complained to me, a good while after, of a violent pain in his Head, which I perceived had omewhat unfitted him for the Tranaction of the Affair whereof he was to be the chief manager. I know another peron, whoe happy Mue hath jutly made him many Admirers, that is ubject to the Head-ach upon o mild a mell as that of Damask-Roes, and ometimes even of Red-Roes, in o much that walking one day with him in a Garden, whoe Alleys were very large, o that he might eaily keep himelf at a ditance from the Buhes, which bore many of them Red-Roes;
he abruptly broke off the dicoure we were engag'd in, to complain of the harm the Perfume did his Head, and deired me to pas into a Walk, that had no Roes growing near it.

Other Examples may be given of the etled difference of Effluviums directly perceivable by Humane Organs of Sene, as dull as they are;
which lat expreion I add, becaue I carce doubt, but that, if our Senories were ufficiently ubtile and tender, they might immediately perceive in the ize, hape, motion, and perhaps colour too of ome now inviible Effluviums, as ditinguihable differences, as our naked Eyes in their preent contitution ee, between the differing orts of Birds, by their appearances, and their manner of flying in the Air, as Hawks, and Partridges, and Sparrows, and Swallows. To make this probable I will not urge, that in fine white Sand, whoe grains by the unaited Eye are not wont to be ditinguihed by any enible Quality, I have often oberv'd in an excellent Microcope, a notable diparity as to bulk, figure, and ometimes as to colour: And that in mall Cheee-mites, which the naked Eye can very carcely dicern, o far is it from dicovering any difference between them, one may (as was noted in the lat eay) plainly ee, beides an obvious difference in point of bignes,
many particular parts, on whoe accounts the tructure of thoe moving points may difference them from each other. And I have ometimes een a very evident diparity even in point of hape between the very Eggs of thee living Atoms, (as a Poet would perhaps tile them.) But thee kinds of proofs (as I was aying) I hall forbear to init on, that I may proceed to countenance my conjecture by the effects of the Effluviums, that are properly o call'd, upon Animals.

To compas then, what I aim'd at, I thought, 'twas fit in the firt place to try, what I could do by the Union of the Sun-beams, they being on all hands confes'd to be Portions (as I may o peak) of true and Celetial Light: And then, I thought fit to try, what could be obtain'd from Flame; not only becaue
that is acknowledg'd to be a Luminary but becaue I hoped, the difficulties, I foreaw in the other Tryals, might be in ome meaure avoided in thoe made with Flame; and if both orts of them hould ucceed, the later and former would erve to confirm each other. According to the Method I propoed of handling thee two Subjects, I hould begin with ome account of what I attempted to perform in the Sun-beams: But the truth is, that when I chanc'd to fall upon the Enquiry that occaion'd this Paper, beides that the time of the Year it elf was not over-favourable, the weather proved o extraordinary dark and uneaonable that it was wonder'd at; o that, though I was furnih'd with good Burning-glaes, and did everal times begin to make tryals upon divers Bodies, as Lead, Quickilver, Antimony, &c. yet the frequent interpoition of Clouds and Mits did o difavour my Attempts, that, however they were not all alike defeated, yet I could not proecute the greatet part of them to my own atisfaction. And therefore being unwilling to build on them as yet;
I hall reerve an account of them for another opportunity; and now proceed to the mention of that ort of Experiments which depending les on Caualities, 'twas more in my power to bring to an Iue.

